Basic HTML Structure

<!DOCTYPE html>: Tells the browser it's an HTML5 document.
<html>: The root element, containing everything.
<head>: Metadata (information about the page).
<body>: The visible content of the page.

Visual: 
		
    <!DOCTYPE html>
    <html>
      <head>
        <title>My Webpage</title>
      </head>
      <body>
        
      </body>
    </html>


  I. Document Structure Tags
    These tags define the overall structure of your HTML document.
    <!DOCTYPE html>: Declaration that defines the document type and version of HTML being used (HTML5).

    <html >: The root element of an HTML page. All other elements are descendants of this tag.

    <head>: Contains meta-information about the HTML document, such as the title, character set, linked stylesheets, etc. This information is not displayed on the page itself.
      <head>
        <title>My Webpage</title>
        <meta charset="UTF-8">
      </head>


    <body>: Contains the visible page content (text, images, videos, etc.).
      <body>
        <h1>Welcome to my website!</h1>
      </body>

      <tags>: these are the tags.

  II. Text Content Tags
    <h1> to <h6>: Heading tags. These tags are used to structure and format text content.
    <h1> represents the most important heading, 
    while <h6> represents the least important.

    <h1>Main Heading</h1>
    <h2>Subheading</h2>
    <h3>Section Heading</h3>

    <p>: Paragraph tag. Used to define a block of text.
      <p>This is a paragraph of text. It can contain multiple sentences.</p>

    <a>: Anchor tag. Creates a hyper-link to other web pages or resources.
      <a href="https://www.google.com">Visit Example</a>

    <span>: Inline container used to mark up a part of a text or a part of a document. It has no required attributes, but style and class are common.
      <p>
        This is a 
        <span style="color:red;">
          red
        </span>
         word.
      </p>

    <b>Bold</b>
    <strong>: Defines important text (usually displayed as bold).
      <p>This is <strong>important</strong> text.</p>

    <i>italic</i>
    <em>: Defines emphasized text (usually displayed as italic).
      <p>This is <em>emphasized</em> text.</p>

    <br>: Line break. Inserts a single line break.
      <p>
        This is the first line.
        <br>
        This is the second line.
      </p>



  III. List Tags
  These tags are used to create ordered and unordered lists.
    <ul>: Unordered list (bulleted list).

      <ul>
        <li>Item 1</li>
        <li>Item 2</li>
        <li>Item 3</li>
      </ul>


    <ol>: Ordered list (numbered list).
    
      <ol>
        <li>First step</li>
        <li>Second step</li>
        <li>Third step</li>
      </ol>


    <li>: List item. Defines an item within a list (<ul> or <ol>).


  IV. Media Tags
    These tags are used to embed multimedia content.
    <img>: Image tag. Embeds an image in the document.

      <img src="myimage.jpg" alt="Description of my image">


    <video>: Video tag. Embeds a video in the document.
    
      <video width="320" height="240" controls>
          <source src="myvideo.mp4" type="video/mp4">
          Your browser does not support the video tag.
      </video>


    <audio>:1 Audio tag. Embeds audio content in the document.

    <audio controls>
        <source src="myaudio.mp3" type="audio/mpeg">
        Your browser does not support the audio element.
    </audio>


  V. Structural Tags
    These tags are used to define sections and structure of the HTML document.
    <div>: Division tag. Defines a section or division in an HTML document. Often used as a container for other elements.

      <div id="header">
          <h1>Website Header</h1>
      </div>
      <div class="content">
          <p>Some content here.</p>
      </div>

      <div> xyz </ div>

      <header>: Represents the header of a section or page.

        <header>
            <h1>Website Title</h1>
            <nav>...</nav>
        </header>


      <footer>: Represents the footer of a section or page.

        <footer>
            <p>Copyright 2024</p>
        </footer>


      <nav>: Represents a section of navigation links.
      
        <nav>
            <a href="#">Home</a>
            <a href="#">About</a>
            <a href="#">Contact</a>
        </nav>


      <article>: Represents a self-contained composition in a document, page, application, or site, which is intended to be independently distributable or reusable (e.g., in syndication).

        <article>
            <h2>Article Title</h2>
            <p>Article content...</p>
        </article>


      <section>: Represents a thematic grouping of content, typically with a heading.

        <section>
            <h2>Section Title</h2>
            <p>Section content...</p>
        </section>


  VI. Table Tags
    These tags are used to create tables for displaying tabular data.
    <table>: Defines a table.

        <table>
            <tr>
                <th>Name</th>                 <th>Age</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>John Doe</td>             <td>30</td>
            </tr>
        </table>


      <tr>: Table row. Defines a row in a table.
      <th>: Table header. Defines a header cell in a table.
      <td>: Table data. Defines a data cell in a table.


  VII. Form Tags
    These tags are used to create HTML forms for user input.
    <form>: Defines an HTML form for user input.
    
      <form action="/submit" method="post">
          <label for="name">Name:</label>
          <br>
          <input type="text" id="name" name="name">
          <br>
          <input type="submit" value="Submit">

          <button type="submit">Submit</button>
      </form>


      <input>: Defines an input field for user input (text, password, checkbox, radio button, etc.).
      <label>: Defines a label for an input element.
      <button>: Defines a clickable button.



