1. Elements
      In HTML, an element is a piece of content in an HTML document. It is defined by a start tag, some content, and an end tag.
      Start Tag: Marks the beginning of the element (e.g., <p>).
      Content: The actual text, images, or other elements within the element.
      End Tag: Marks the end of the element (e.g., </p>).


      <p>
        This is a paragraph element.
      </p>

      <h1>
        This is a heading element.
      </h1>


2. Nesting Tags and Elements
      Nesting means placing one HTML element inside another. This creates a hierarchical structure in your document. Proper nesting is crucial for correct HTML.
      Correct Nesting:
        <div>
            <p>This paragraph is inside a div.</p>
        </div>


      Incorrect Nesting (Overlapping):
        <div>
            <p>This is <div>incorrect</div> nesting.</p>
        </div>


      In the incorrect example, the <div> tag is opened inside the <p> tag but closed outside. This will lead to unpredictable behavior and must be avoided.


3. Attributes
        Attributes provide additional information about HTML elements. They are always specified in the start tag of an element and consist of a name and a value.

        Syntax: attribute_name="attribute_value"

        <a href="https://www.example.com" target="_blank">Visit Example</a>
        <img src="image.jpg" alt="A descriptive image" width="500" height="300">


      Common Attributes:
      href: Specifies the URL of a link (<a>).
      src: Specifies the source of an image (<img>), video (<video>), or audio (<audio>).
      alt: Specifies alternative text for an image (<img>). Important for accessibility.
      width and height: Specify the width and height of an image or video.
      class: Specifies one or more class names for an element. Used for styling with CSS.
      id: Specifies a unique ID for an element. Used for styling with CSS or scripting with JavaScript.
      style: Specifies inline styles for an element (less recommended, prefer external CSS).
      title: Provides a tooltip when hovering over the element.


4. Void Elements (Self-Closing Tags)
    Void elements, also known as self-closing tags or empty elements, do not have closing tags. They only have a start tag and usually use a trailing slash / .
        Examples:
        <br>: Line break.
        <hr>: Horizontal rule (line).
        <img>: Image.
        <input>: Input field.
        <meta>: Metadata.
        <link>: Links external resources (like CSS stylesheets).
      Example:
        <br />
        <hr /> 
        <img src="image.jpg" alt="Image" />
        <input type="text" name="username" />
        <meta charset="UTF-8" />
        <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css" />


5. Entities (Character Entities or HTML Entities)
      HTML entities are used to display reserved characters in HTML that would otherwise be interpreted as HTML code. They are also useful for displaying characters that are not easily typed on a keyboard.
      
      Syntax: 	&entity_name;         or         &#entity_number;

          Common Entities:
          <: Less than (<)
          >: Greater than (>)
          &: Ampersand (&)
          ": Double quote (")
          ': Apostrophe (')
          : Non-breaking space

      <p>10 < 20</p>
      <p>This is a "quoted" string.</p> 
      <p>This is a "quoted" string.</p> 
      <p>This   is   spaced   out.</p>

                                                           
